</div><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/thr/news/~4/ipt9SaPBMNU" height="1" width="1">";s:9:"feed_link";s:33:"http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/";s:10:"feed_title";s:18:"Hollywood Reporter";}s:32:"ec6572d5188ee399a2c06294881cae27";a:7:{s:5:"title";s:87:"Google's One Today app for Android lets you donate $1 to select nonprofit organizations";s:4:"link";s:64:"http://www.engadget.com/2013/04/19/google-one-today-charity-app/";s:6:"author";s:10:"Mark Hearn";s:4:"date";i:1366321680;s:7:"content";s:2206:"<p> <a href="http://www.engadget.com/2013/04/19/google-one-today-charity-app/"><img alt="DNP Google's One Today app for Android lets you donate $1 to select nonprofit organizations" data-src-height="350" data-src-width="619" src="http://www.blogcdn.com/www.engadget.com/media/2013/04/giving.jpg"></a></p><p> Google may be raking in the <a href="http://www.engadget.com/2013/04/18/google-q1-2013-earnings-14-billion-in-revenue-3-35-billion/">dough</a>, but that doesn't mean the company is lacking a social conscience. Yesterday, the software giant silently released its One Today app for Android. Available in the US by invite only, the setup features a daily profile on a different nonprofit project and gives you the option to donate $1 to its cause. Payments require a <a href="http://www.engadget.com/2012/08/01/google-wallet-moves-to-the-cloud-opens-up-to-all-credit-and-deb/">Google Wallet</a> account and gifting is currently limited to a buck per day. If you're looking to raise more capital for a specific cause, you can challenge friends via social networks to donate and then match their donations (up to a point). After all, this is about bringing networks of people together to bolster the spirit of giving. Check out the adjacent source link to apply for an app invite.</p><p>Filed under: <a href="http://www.engadget.com/category/software/" rel="tag">Software</a>, <a href="http://www.engadget.com/category/mobile/" rel="tag">Mobile</a>, <a href="http://www.engadget.com/category/google/" rel="tag">Google</a></p><p><strong><a href="http://www.engadget.com/2013/04/19/google-one-today-charity-app/#comments">Comments</a></strong></p><p><strong>Via:</strong> <a target="_blank" href="http://www.theverge.com/2013/4/18/4240894/google-one-today-brings-app-store-scale-to-charitable-donating">The Verge</a><!--//--></p><p><strong>Source:</strong> <a target="_blank" href="https://www.google.com/onetoday/">One Today</a><!--//-->, <a target="_blank" href="https://plus.google.com/u/0/103005635067741407907/posts/8Mgpq4CdxM1">Google Giving (Google+)</a><!--//-->, <a target="_blank" href="https://play.google.com/store/apps/details?id=com.google.android.apps.onetoday">Google Play</a><!--//--></p>";s:9:"feed_link";s:24:"http://www.engadget.com/";s:10:"feed_title";s:17:"Engadget RSS Feed";}s:32:"b9e65265f4f91195bdfa8c793f8646b8";a:7:{s:5:"title";s:63:"Boston Marathon Bombing: FBI Releases Suspect Images on Live TV";s:4:"link";s:98:"http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/thr/news/~3/UpewK_ACfpY/boston-marathon-bombing-fbi-releases-442256";s:6:"author";s:11:"Erik Hayden";s:4:"date";i:1366321398;s:7:"content";s:1700:"<img src="http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/sites/default/files/2013/04/boston_bombing_suspects_a_l.jpg"><br>At a Thursday press conference, the FBI released photos of two suspects.<p><a href="http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/boston-marathon-bombing-fbi-releases-442256" target="_blank">read more</a></p><div>
