</div><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/thr/news/~4/bVrNywax0PY" height="1" width="1">";s:9:"feed_link";s:33:"http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/";s:10:"feed_title";s:18:"Hollywood Reporter";}s:32:"542e7857ad13449961eddecede55d82f";a:7:{s:5:"title";s:82:"Ricoh unveils $800 GR compact with 16-megapixel APS-C sensor, continuous autofocus";s:4:"link";s:91:"http://www.engadget.com/2013/04/17/ricoh-unveils-16-megapixel-gr-compact-with-aps-c-sensor/";s:6:"author";s:10:"Steve Dent";s:4:"date";i:1366153980;s:7:"content";s:1588:"<p> <a href="http://www.engadget.com/2013/04/17/ricoh-unveils-16-megapixel-gr-compact-with-aps-c-sensor/"><img alt="Ricoh unveils 16megapixel GR compact with APSC sensor, f28 lens" data-src-height="340" data-src-width="620" src="http://www.blogcdn.com/www.engadget.com/media/2013/04/ricoh-gr-04-17-13-02.jpg"></a></p><p> Though it's a bit late to the large-sensor compact game, Ricoh just jumped into the fray with a model that might tempt the high-end grab and go set: the GR. Following in a trail blazed by the likes of <a href="http://www.engadget.com/2012/09/12/sony-cyber-shot-rx1-compact-camera-packs-a-full-frame-senso/">Sony</a> and Nikon with its <a href="http://www.engadget.com/2013/03/04/nikon-dx-format-coolpix-a/">Coolipix A</a>, Ricoh's new advanced compact packs very similar specs to the latter: a 16-megapixel APS-C-sized sensor, fixed 18.3 mm f/2.8 lens, ISO 25,600 capability, pop-up flash, Eye-Fi card compatibility, 1080 / 30p AF video and 4 fps shooting with continuous autofocus for "fast-moving subjects." The similarities end with the price, however, since Ricoh is offering the GR for $800 compared to $1,100 for the Nikon, and has eschewed the optical low-pass filter to increase sharpness and further tempt high-end shooters. You'll be able to grab one stateside next month -- check the PR after the break for more.</p><p>Filed under: <a href="http://www.engadget.com/category/cameras/" rel="tag">Cameras</a></p><p><strong><a href="http://www.engadget.com/2013/04/17/ricoh-unveils-16-megapixel-gr-compact-with-aps-c-sensor/#comments">Comments</a></strong></p>";s:9:"feed_link";s:24:"http://www.engadget.com/";s:10:"feed_title";s:17:"Engadget RSS Feed";}s:32:"39243fe9da7a5e56cf5f866385d223a3";a:7:{s:5:"title";s:35:"Toh Kay: With Any Sort Of Certainty";s:4:"link";s:89:"http://feeds.gawker.com/~r/gizmodo/full/~3/8A-w8aqXDgA/toh-kay-with-any-sort-of-certainty";s:6:"author";s:16:"Andrew Tarantola";s:4:"date";i:1366153200;s:7:"content";s:3343:"<div> <!-- div style="background-color: #B3B3B3; width: 190px; padding: 1px;"><a title="Click here to read Toh Kay: With Any Sort Of Certainty" href="http://gizmodo.com/soundtrack/" style="background-color:#888888; color:#FFFFFF; font-size:12px;text-align:right; display:block; height:14px; padding:1px 2px; text-decoration:none; text-transform:uppercase; width:156px;"><span style="color: white;" class="hash">#</span><span style="color: white;">soundtrack</span></a></div --> <div><a title="Click here to read Toh Kay: With Any Sort Of Certainty" href="http://gizmodo.com/5994726/toh-kay-with-any-sort-of-certainty"> <img height="360" width="640" title="Click here to read Toh Kay: With Any Sort Of Certainty" alt="Click here to read Toh Kay: With Any Sort Of Certainty" src="http://img.gawkerassets.com/img/18kqwrni16ioqjpg/xlarge.jpg"><span></span> </a></div> </div> <!-- videoId: 62678089 --><!-- /videoId: 62678089 --> This is, as animator Scott Benson puts it, "A story about not being OK, and trying to be." But who's to say what constitutes OK? Is it akin to childhood innocence&mdash;that which, once stripped, can never be revived? Or is it a more transient state of being, countering the gnawing pain of regret and self-doubt? <a href="http://gizmodo.com/5994726/toh-kay-with-any-sort-of-certainty" title="Click here to read more about Toh Kay: With Any Sort Of Certainty">More&nbsp;&raquo;</a> <br><img width="1" height="1" src="http://gizmodo.feedsportal.com/c/34976/f/647164/s/2acc