gadget-hd-podcast-345-04-16-13/"><img alt="Engadget HD Podcast 345 - 04.16.13" src="http://www.blogcdn.com/www.engadget.com/media/2012/12/eng-podcast-hd-620_620x340.jpg"></a></p><p> 4K TVs for less than $1,500? That's the new world we live in, as we dive into Ultra HD, next Xbox rumors and more on this week's podcast. Meanwhile, news of the death of Panasonic plasma R&amp;D program was apparently greatly exaggerated, so we'll figure out what to expect from the manufacturer in the future. Finally, we've got a fresh update in the always interesting news category of Dish Network Does Things.</p><p> <strong>Host</strong><strong>s</strong>: Ben Drawbaugh (<a href="http://www.twitter.com/bjdraw">@bjdraw</a>), Richard Lawler (<a href="http://twitter.com/rjcc">@rjcc</a>)</p><p> <strong>Producer</strong>: James Trew (<a href="http://twitter.com/itstrew">@itstrew</a>)</p><p> <strong>Hear the podcast</strong></p><p>Filed under: <a href="http://www.engadget.com/category/podcasts/" rel="tag">Podcasts</a>, <a href="http://www.engadget.com/category/hd/" rel="tag">HD</a></p><p><strong><a href="http://www.engadget.com/2013/04/16/engadget-hd-podcast-345-04-16-13/#comments">Comments</a></strong></p>";s:9:"feed_link";s:24:"http://www.engadget.com/";s:10:"feed_title";s:17:"Engadget RSS Feed";}s:32:"604176f5093f1dbd312e9b9c4eac2fce";a:7:{s:5:"title";s:25:"LIFE Fash. story | Ningbo";s:4:"link";s:61:"http://www.behance.net/gallery/LIFE-Fash-story-Ningbo/8032125";s:6:"author";s:0:"";s:4:"date";i:1366129802;s:7:"content";s:164:"<img src="http://behance.vo.llnwd.net/profiles18/256493/projects/8032125/d0a3aba7e1c2b4661e273eab437af9f5.jpg"><br> a fashion story done for LIFE magazine in Ningbo";s:9:"feed_link";s:23:"http://www.behance.net/";s:10:"feed_title";s:25:"Behance Featured Projects";}s:32:"fda53b409f3b08aa7e0020bd3dd3e82c";a:7:{s:5:"title";s:76:"Jolla's reportedly launching a handset with 'Scandinavian design' next month";s:4:"link";s:62:"http://www.engadget.com/2013/04/16/jolla-first-handset-launch/";s:6:"author";s:13:"Edgar Alvarez";s:4:"date";i:1366129620;s:7:"content";s:2281:"<p> <a href="http://www.engadget.com/2013/04/16/jolla-first-handset-launch/"><img alt="Jolla's reportedly launching a handset with 'Scandinavian design' next month" data-src-height="372" data-src-width="620" src="http://www.blogcdn.com/www.engadget.com/media/2013/04/jolla416-1366150066.jpg"></a></p><p> This year's <a href="http://www.engadget.com/event/mwc2013/articles/">Mobile World Congress</a> was a rather meaningful one for Jolla, what with the launch of its <a href="http://www.engadget.com/2013/04/05/sailfish-sdk-out-now/">Sailfish OS SDK</a>. But what's an operating system without a <a href="http://www.engadget.com/2012/12/29/hands-on-with-jollas-sailfish-os-video/"><em>proper</em></a> fixture, right? To wit, <em>DigiToday</em> is reporting that the team of ex-MeeGo engineers is getting ready to debut its first hardware early next month -- a handset emblematic of a "modern Scandinavian design," according to Jolla Chairman Antti Saarnio. Further, the Finnish news site says <a href="http://www.engadget.com/tag/jolla/">Jolla's</a> taking a cue from the recent crowd-funded craze: it's prepping limited edition versions of the device for early adopters. Naturally, we'll have to wait for something more concrete, but with May just around the corner, it shouldn't be too long before we can finally see what Jolla has <a href="http://www.engadget.com/2013/03/03/the-engadget-interview-jolla-ceo-marc-dillon-at-mwc-2013/">in store for us</a>.</p><p>Filed under: <a href="http://www.engadget.com/category/cellphones/" rel="tag">Cellphones</a>, <a href="http://www.engadget.com/category/wireless/" rel="tag">Wireless</a>, <a href="http://www.engadget.com/category/software/" rel="tag">Software</a>, <a href="http://www.engadget.com/category/mobile/" rel="tag">Mobile</a></p><p><strong><a href="http://www.engadget.com/2013/04/16/jolla-first-handset-launch/#comments">Comments</a></strong></p><p><strong>Via:</strong> <a target="_blank" href="http://mynokiablog.com/2013/04/16/jolla-to-announce-first-device-in-may-pre-order-for-special-edition-variant/">My Nokia Blog</a><!--//--></p><p><strong>Source:</strong> <a target="_blank" href="http://www.digitoday.fi/mobiili/2013/04/16/ennakkotilaajat-saavat-hienomman-jolla-puhelimen/20135494/66">DigiToday</a><!--//--></p>";s:9:"feed_link";s:24:"http://www.engadget.com/";s:10:"feed_title";s:17:"Engadget RSS Feed";}s:32:"429d2fa779c1718533d105315483e335";a:7:{s:5:"title";s:32:"The Daily Roundup for 04.16.2013";s:4:"link";s:68:"http://www.engadget.com/2013/04/16/the-daily-roundup-for-04-16-2013/";s:6:"author";s:13:"David Fishman";s:4:"date";i:1366127160;s:7:"content";s:728:"<!-- Content --><p> <a href="http://www.engadget.com/2013/04/16/the-daily-roundup-for-04-16-2013/"><img alt="DNP The Daily RoundUp" data-src-height="200" data-src-width="620" src="http://www.blogcdn.com/www.engadget.com/media/2012/11/dailyroundup4.png"></a></p><p> <em>You might say the day is never really done in consumer technology news. Your workday, however, hopefully draws to a close at some point. This is the Daily Roundup on Engadget, a quick peek back at the top headlines for the past 24 hours -- all handpicked by the editors here at the site. Click on through the break, and enjoy.</em></p><p><strong><a href="http://www.engadget.com/2013/04/16/the-daily-roundup-for-04-16-2013/#comments">Comments</a></strong></p>";s:9:"feed_link";s:24:"http://www.engadget.com/";s:10:"feed_title";s:17:"Engadget RSS Feed";}s:32:"6d3b59f795135490527ffe47b453ba33";a:7:{s:5:"title";s:65:"Chrome for Business adds legacy browser support, cloud management";s:4:"link";s:62:"http://www.engadget.com/2013/04/16/chrome-for-business-update/";s:6:"author";s:10:"Nicole Lee";s:4:"date";i:1366125420;s:7:"content";s:1744:"<p> <a href="http://www.engadget.com/2013/04/16/chrome-for-business-update/"><img alt="Chrome for Business adds legacy browser support, cloud management" data-src-height="360" data-src-width="603" src="http://www.blogcdn.com/www.engadget.com/media/2013/04/businesschrome.jpg"></a></p><p> Not one to leave its <a href="http://www.engadget.com/2012/12/07/google-apps-discontinues-basic-package/">business</a> <a href="http://www.engadget.com/2012/10/30/google-enterprise-partner-search/">customers</a> out of the loop, Google updated its Chrome for Business browser today with a couple of new features: <span>legacy browser support and cloud-based management for Google Apps. With the former, those who are obliged to use older apps at work (poor you) will be automatically switched to an alternate browser when needed, while the cloud-based management allows employees to log in to their Google Apps for Business or Education accounts from any device. Of course, both features require the approval of your friendly neighborhood IT administrator, so do remember to offer him or her a token of appreciation the next time their <a href="http://www.engadget.com/2011/07/29/system-administrator-appreciation-day-is-here-show-them-some-lo/">special day</a> rolls around. </span></p><p>Filed under: <a href="http://www.engadget.com/category/internet/" rel="tag">Internet</a>, <a href="http://www.engadget.com/category/google/" rel="tag">Google</a></p><p><strong><a href="http://www.engadget.com/2013/04/16/chrome-for-business-update/#comments">Comments</a></strong></p><p><strong>Source:</strong> <a target="_blank" href="http://googleenterprise.blogspot.com/2013/04/new-chrome-features-bring-modern-web-to.html">Google Enterprise blog</a><!--//--></p>";s:9:"feed_link";s:24:"http://www.engadget.com/";s:10:"feed_title";s:17:"Engadget RSS Feed";}s:32:"0b63f352d9231cd36045aee572554cf6";a:7:{s:5:"title";s:38:"This That Other by Stefan Diez for e15";s:4:"link";s:53:"http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/dezeen/~3/4ekrHLIGKBU/";s:6:"author";s:16:"Emilie Chalcraft";s:4:"date";i:1366124429;s:7:"content";s:1559:"<p><a href="http://www.dezeen.com/2013/04/16/this-that-other-by-stefan-diez-for-e15/">
	          <img src="http://static.dezeen.com/uploads/2013/04/dezeen_This-That-Other-by-Stefan-Diaz-for-e15_1a.jpg"></a></p>
